I failed with https://developer.atlassian.com/display/CONFDEV/Write+an+intermediate+blueprint+plugin , having had no problem with the first ("simple") tutorial.  I eventually restarted and downloaded the completed git, and discovered that the code you had written was for 5.1.4, although there are indications that the tutorial was updated for 5.3, and if you start the plugin as described in the "Simple" tutorial you will be using 5.4.  I believe (though I'm not sure, since the working code in the git uses 5.1) the problem is that the code tries to subclass a blueprint class that isn't there in 5.4, so it wouldn't work.  However, I can't be sure, since there's no version information in the tutorial.

As pretty much a Java newbie, I want to point out that Java is a language with very complex structures of files and dependencies, and in a case like this it is virtually impossible to figure out what the problem is.  You really need to indicate to your users which versions work with the code in the tutorial, so learners (and who else would be using a tutorial?) can have some hope of understanding whether they've made some mistake that needs to be tracked down, or there's a version problem.

I noticed that the pom.xml file in the downloaded code specified the Confluence version, and Maven automatically downloaded that and built to it.  You could provide a step to modify the POM (to specify a Confluence version) so that the tutorial user can be sure she is using a version of the Confluence code that works with the code in the supplied tutorial.

